<HEADLINE>
FT  10 APR 92 / Payroll group sold after tax payments go astray
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD GOURLAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
JAPANESE banks, already reeling as the Japanese economy falters, are among
500 companies in the UK facing a total loss of up to Pounds 20m following
the discovery that PAYE and national insurance payments have gone astray on
the way to the Inland Revenue.
The financial institutions, including Fuji International and Yamaichi
International, were all clients of Payroll Services, a private company that
handled about Pounds 30m a month in payroll, PAYE and NI payments.
Touche Ross, the accountancy firm, has been appointed to act as provisional
liquidator at Payroll Services, and its parent, Wren Group, after the Inland
Revenue discovered one of the institutions was behind on its tax payments.
The UK's largest banks, which have their own payroll departments, are not
believed to be involved. But Payroll Services' client list reads like a
Who's Who of international banking. Payroll Services also paid the salaries
of the London-based crews of Japan Air Lines, which estimates it will have
to pay Pounds 250,000 again to the Inland Revenue to cover missing PAYE and
NI contributions.
This amount was described by one client, who wished to remain anonymous, as
'small fry' compared with the losses facing other companies.
Industrial Bank of Japan said last night it had not suffered any financial
damage, having stopped using Payroll Services for making payments last
November. Visa International, one of Payroll Services' biggest clients, and
Nippon Credit International, said they had stopped using Payroll Services
last year. Another large Japanese bank had made credit checks on Payroll
Services and was about to segregate its payments. However, Payroll Services
failed before a trustee account could be set up.
The Inland Revenue has agreed to give Payroll Services' clients a moratorium
of a few weeks on paying the missing taxes while Touche Ross establishes how
much is missing. The Inland Revenue has made clear, however, that in such
cases it still looks to the banks and companies for payment of the taxes.
The Pounds 20m believed to be missing is an initial estimate and sources
close to the company believe it could be much higher.
Touche Ross is investigating all the circumstances surrounding its
appointment and has reached no conclusions on why the money has gone
missing.
Touche Ross said all the directors of Wren Group and Payroll Services had
left the company. Mr Terence Wright, who holds all but one of Payroll
Services' 5,000 shares, could not be contacted.
Yesterday, Touche Ross said a consortium of Payroll Services' clients had
bought its goodwill and equipment for a sum understood to be about Pounds
1m.
</TEXT>
