<HEADLINE>
FT  10 APR 92 / Election 1992: Election night countdown
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
10.00: BBC Election '92 predicts hung parliament, with the Conservatives 10
short of an overall majority.
10.05: ITN/Harris poll shows Labour and the Conservatives much closer in
marginal constituencies.
10.29: Mrs Margaret Thatcher, questioned by the BBC on her return from US.
says: 'It looks hopeful. I am quite optimistic.'
10.38: Responding to the BBC's exit poll, shadow environment secretary Mr
Bryan Gould said the result showed the biggest swing to Labour since 1945.
10.53: Stockbroking service ShareLink reported brisk business following the
exit polls, with investors buying across the board.
11.07: First results: Labour holds Sunderland South (2 per cent swing to
Labour as Chris Mullin is re-elected). Rupert Allason holds Torbay for
Conservatives.
11.23: Tory David Amess holds marginal Basildon with an increased majority.
Swing to Labour is 1.3 per cent.
11.37: First recount - at Portsmouth South. The Tories later held the seat
by 242 votes.
00.03: Wrexham result shows Labour holds seat with increased majority and
2.4 per cent swing from Conservative to Labour.
00.14: Liberal Democrats capture Cheltenham from Conservatives. Mr Nigel
Jones, Lib Dem victor, denies the race issue had helped to defeat Mr John
Taylor, black Conservative candidate.
00.27: Labour captures Nuneaton from the Conservatives with a 7 per cent
swing.
00.34: Mr David Mellor, chief secretary to the Treasury, first member of the
cabinet to be re-elected, with an increased majority at Putney, London.
00.45: Mr Dave Nellist, (pictured) who was expelled from Labour party for
his alleged links with Militant, narrowly defeated by official Labour
candidate in Coventry South East.
00.54: Scottish National party suffers stinging reverse as Mr Jim Sillars,
deputy leader, loses his Govan seat - recaptured by Labour.
01.09: First ministerial casualty. Mr Michael Fallon, junior education
minister, defeated in Darlington. Five per cent swing from Conservative to
Labour.
01.20: Mr Edward Heath, former prime minister, re-elected as Conservative MP
for Old Bexley and Sidcup and becomes father of the House of Commons.
01.26: Michael Forsyth, controversial Scottish health minister, holds
Stirling.
01.38: Mr Chris Patten, Tory party chairman, loses Bath - the third Liberal
Democrat gain of the night.
01.49: Overseas development minister Lynda Chalker loses her Wallasey seat
on Merseyside to Labour, but a Conservative majority of five seats is
predicted.
01.51: Plaid Cymru wins Ceredigion and Pembroke North by unseating Liberal
Democrat Mr Geraint Howells.
01.55: Labour gains Ellesmere Port and Neston and Barrow in Furness
</TEXT>
