<HEADLINE>
FT  10 APR 92 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow boosted as Fed eases
monetary policy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US STOCK markets rebounded from two days of heavy losses, aided by good news
on inflation and an easing in monetary policy by the Federal Reserve, writes
Patrick Harverson in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average finished 43.61 up at 3,224.96, although off
its high for the day when the index had been ahead more than 50 points. The
Standard &amp; Poor's 500 forged ahead 6.14 to 400.64, while the Nasdaq
composite index of over-the-counter stocks soared 13.07 to 586.75. Turnover
on the New York SE was again heavy at 231m shares and rises outpaced falls
by 1,271 to 494.
Share prices opened firmer, but did not take off until 11.30am, when the Fed
eased, by signalling to the credit markets that it wanted the Fed Funds rate
brought down from 4 per cent to 3 3/4 per cent. The Fed's action was
interpreted primarily as an attempt to boost the economy.
Room was made for a monetary easing by the morning's inflation figures,
which showed that producer prices rose just 0.2 per cent in March,
indicating that inflationary pressures remained dormant.
There were some big gains among leading stocks which bore the brunt of
Tuesday and Wednesday's selling. Merck gained Dollars 3 5/8 to Dollars 150
1/8 , General Electric rose Dollars 1 7/8 to Dollars 74 3/4 , Philip Morris
firmed Dollars  1/2 to Dollars 75 7/8 and Procter &amp; Gamble advanced Dollars
2 1/4 to Dollars 98 3/4 .
Banking issues, which have suffered from concern about a Japanese financial
crisis, recovered strongly. JP Morgan rose Dollars 3 1/2 to Dollars 55 7/8 ,
aided by an upgrade from a 'hold' to a 'buy' recommendation from Brown
Brothers Harriman. Bankers Trust firmed Dollars 1 3/4 to Dollars 53 1/8 ,
Citicorp gained Dollars  7/8 to Dollars 16 1/8 and Chemical put on Dollars 1
to Dollars 30 1/2 .
One of the rare losers was Digital Equipment, which dropped Dollars 5 1/4 to
Dollars 48 1/4 after reporting a fiscal third-quarter loss of Dollars 294m,
compared with a profit at the same stage last year of Dollars 117m. News of
higher March sales lifted retailers JC Penney Dollars 2 5/8 to Dollars 65,
Sears Dollars  7/8 to Dollars 45 1/2 , Dayton Hudson Dollars 2 5/8 to
Dollars 62 5/8 and K Mart Dollars 2 3/8 to Dollars 52.
Fannie Mae moved ahead Dollars 2 1/8 to Dollars 65 1/8 on news of a 13 per
cent rise in first-quarter profits to a record Dollars 381.6m.
Canada
TORONTO stocks quickly picked up from a flat opening after the US Federal
Reserve cut its funds rate target, sending the market sharply higher. The
upturn reversed two straight days of losses in the market totalling 68
points on the 300-share composite index.
The index closed 30.9 up at 3,349.0, while advances led declines by 310 to
237 after volume of 27.7m shares.
Canadian banks quickly followed the US Fed's move with cuts to their prime
rates to 8 per cent from 8.25.
