<HEADLINE>
FT  10 APR 92 / International Company News: Injunction granted against
Blockbuster
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A DALLAS court has granted a temporary injunction against Blockbuster, the
US video rental chain which owns the Cityvision group in the UK, restricting
its activities in certain US east coast areas.
The order follows the filing of a lawsuit against Blockbuster by Capitol
Entertainment, a Blockbuster franchisee and largely owned by the Zale
jewellery store family.
The dispute results from Blockbuster's purchase of the sizeable Erol's Video
Store chain in the US last year. Capitol, whose franchise area encompasses
some of the Erol area, has alleged that Blockbuster promised not to acquire
Erol until it had a deal to sell Capitol the Erol stores in Capitol's
territories; that it went ahead regardless and then offered the stores on
'the most onerous terms'.
A trial date has now been set for January 11, 1993.
However, in the meantime the court found that Blockbuster had 'competed
unfairly' with the plaintiffs, and that there were grounds for restraining
the group's activities in the area.
Blockbuster claimed that 'the court had found no evidence to support Capitol
Entertainment's contention that it had an agreement with the company to
purchase certain Erol's video stores at an agreed-upon price', and heralded
this as 'a major victory'.
</TEXT>
