<HEADLINE>
FT  10 APR 92 / International Company News: American Airlines overhauls
domestic fare structure
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AMERICAN Airlines, one of the three largest US airlines, yesterday unveiled
details of a radical and much-rumoured overhaul in its domestic fare
structure, writes Nikki Tait.
American said that, for domestic travel starting on April 13, it planned to
operate four principal fare classes, with fares generally lower than full
fares for comparable existing classes. First-class fares, for example, would
be 20 to 50 per cent lower than existing full fares for first-class.
On the minus side, the company will discontinue corporate discounts, and
charge a Dollars 25 fee for rescheduling or refunding tickets. The overhaul
will reduce the number of different fares offered from 500,000 to around
70,000.
Some analysts, however, saw move as an implicit attempt to push up fares.
Few travellers pay full coach fares at present, and businesses often find
discount alternatives.
Mr Bob Crandall, American's chairman, stressed that this was not a 'one-off'
promotional scheme, but a fundamental overhaul of pricing policy.
He denied that American was responding to aggressive pricing tactics by
either Southwest Airlines, the smaller carrier also based in Dallas, or
Trans World Airlines, which is in bankruptcy and has been slashing fares to
attract business customers.
Both Delta Air Lines and United Airlines, American's biggest rivals, said
that simplified fares made sense, and pledged to remain competitive.
Northwest Airlines, Continental and America West, a smaller bankrupt
carrier, also said they would adjust fares.
Mr Crandall admitted that American could lose some revenue in the short-term
 -he put the second-quarter figure at around Dollars 100m - but estimated
the long-term annual benefit at Dollars 300m to Dollars 350m.
The simpler structure, he added, could lead to annual cost savings of around
Dollars 25m.
PWA, the parent of Canadian Airlines International, is seeking CDollars 200m
(USDollars 169.5m) cash in return for selling 25 per cent of the airline to
American Airlines.
Analysts had estimated Mr Eyton would seek about CDollars 100m in new equity
for Canadian.
The two companies are now in negotiations.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 27
