</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE official bondholders' committee at Circle K, the bankrupt US convenience
store chain, yesterday filed papers in the Arizona courts opposing aspects
of the proposed sale of the business to a group of investors, writes Nikki
Tait.
The Dollars 425m deal was announced last month. The international group of
investors is led by Investcorp, the Arab finance organisation which already
owns Saks Fifth Avenue.
The bondholders committee alleges that there was lack of informed
decision-making by the board, and claims that the entire board never
received a written valuation of Circle K's worth. As a result, it suggests,
the board could not make an informed decision on the offer and breached its
fiduciary duty.
