<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A FEDERAL bankruptcy court judge will decide today which of two bids to
accept for the aerospace and missiles business of steel group LTV, but his
preliminary remarks last night seemed to favour of consortium of Thomson-CSF
of France and Washington's Carlyle Group.
LTV, which has been operating under the protection of the bankruptcy court
for the past five years, needs the judge's approval for the sale of the
business.
After two days of bidding, Thomson and Carlyle had an offer of Dollars 440m
on the table, while rivals Lockheed and Martin Marietta had one of Dollars
385m.
Each bid has support among various creditors of LTV and other interested
parties.
