<HEADLINE>
FT  10 APR 92 / International Company News: Credit Lyonnais doubles client
risk provisions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CREDIT Lyonnais, one of the largest French banks, yesterday reported a fall
in annual net profits, from FFr3.71bn (Dollars 660m) in 1990 to FFr3.16bn,
after doubling the client risk provisions to FFr9.5bn because of loan
losses.
The fall was disclosed on the same day that the the upper house in the
French parliament ordered an inquiry into the bank.
The inquiry follows a lobby last year by opposition politicians demanding a
formal investigation into Credit Lyonnais' involvement with the ill-fated
takeover of MGM-Pathe, the Hollywood movie studio, by Mr Giancarlo Parretti,
the Italian businessman whom Credit Lyonnais later ousted from MGM.
Mr Jean-Yves Haberer, chairman, said it was too early to comment on the
inquiry. Mr Haberer led Credit Lyonnais' aggressive expansion into new areas
of banking and different countries in the late 1980s.
The findings of the senate inquiries are influential within French political
and industrial circles, but do not have immediate legislative implications.
Credit Lyonnais, which may have to make bigger provisions in 1992 because of
its exposure to Olympia &amp; York, the troubled Canadian property group, raised
its total provisions from FFr6.5bn to FFr9.6bn last year.
Its client risk provisions - thought to include write-offs on loans to VEV,
the troubled French textile group, and Hachette, the struggling publishing
company, as well as on MGM and the companies headed by the late Mr Robert
Maxwell, the UK publisher - rose from FFr4.2bn to FFr9.5bn.
The increase in provisions, to the upper end of analysts' estimates, meant
that net profits fell despite a healthy 13.5 per cent increase in net
banking income, from FFr40.83bn to FFr46.33bn. Mr Haberer said the increase
reflected the strong performance of Credit Lyonnais' retail banking networks
in Europe, and its investment banking interests in the US.
The fall in net profits meant earnings per share slipped from FFr110.6 to
FFr90. However, the board proposed holding the dividend - for the third year
in succession - at FFr34.5 a share.
Mr Haberer said that, despite the increase in provisions and the general
problems posed by the worldwide economic slowdown, he was encouraged by the
progress of Credit Lyonnais' retail networks and by the increased
contribution from its industrial investments.
He said the group was determined to continue its policy of expanding its
European network, and confirmed it was still in discussions over an
investment in Germany's BfG, the troubled union bank belonging to the AMB
insurance company.
</TEXT>
