FT  10 APR 92 / UK Company News: ADT plans ambitious warrant offering
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ADT, the Bermuda-based security and car auction company, set itself an
ambitious target of a 1-for-6 warrant offering at Dollars 10 a share to
existing shareholders in its annual report circulated yesterday.
The report reflects the new standards of corporate governance introduced
after pressure exerted last year by Laidlaw, the Canadian waste services and
school bus operator which holds the majority stake in ADT.
It includes far greater details in the accounts - for the year to December
31 1991 - and a commitment to issue quarterly reports from March 31 1992.
Notes to the accounts reveal that litigation with Laidlaw cost ADT Dollars
11.5m, which Mr Michael Ashcroft, chairman, referred to in his letter to
shareholders as a 'short but distracting legal dispute'.
Goodwill write-offs included Dollars 278m against the acquisition of
Britannia Security Group in 1990 after an extensive review suggesting assets
had been materially overvalued. 'The company is discussing with its advisers
the various courses of action which may be available,' it said.
There are also write-offs of Dollars 146m against Christies International,
Dollars 101m against Lep and Dollars 21m of security services.
Mr Ashcroft said that in spite of attention given to the company's debt
maturities, principal banking facilities do not mature until 1994. He said
ADT continued to be in compliance with its covenants made to bankers and 'it
is not expected that any such covenants will be breached.'
Net cash provided by operating activities has risen to Dollars 218m (Dollars
140m), while net cash outflows from investing have slumped to Dollars 16m
(Dollars 539m).
Aggregate directors' remuneration fell to Dollars 4.9m (Dollars 5.6m), but
included a substantial rise in directors' shareholdings, including 1.75m
beneficial and 908,000 options held by Mr Ashcroft.
