<HEADLINE>
FT  10 APR 92 / Election 1992: SNP suffers severe blow in Govan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Scottish National party suffered a severe blow early this morning when
Mr Jim Sillars, the party's deputy leader, lost his Glasgow Govan seat to
Labour.
Labour's Mr Ian Davidson took the seat that Mr Sillars won in a sensational
by-election in 1988.
The SNP also failed to take Western Isles, a seat it had held until losing
it to Labour in 1987. In other early results in safe Labour seats the swing
to the SNP was less than the party had hoped.
However, the Nationalists still hoped to win three seats from the
Conservatives including that of Mr Ian Lang, the Scottish secretary, while
Labour was also expected to take seats from the Tories.
The Conservatives rallied, however, winning Aberdeen South from Labour after
the Labour vote was eroded by the SNP, and regaining Kincardine and Deeside,
its recent by-election loss to the Liberal Democrats.
Mr Michael Forsyth, the junior Scottish Office minister, held Stirling
against a strong Labour challenge.
The SNP and Labour hopes of gains against the Tories were based on
projections of the original BBC exit poll. If realised, they would plunge
Scotland into a constitutional crisis with the Tories suffering a near
wipeout in Scotland while remaining the largest single party in the United
Kingdom with Mr Major staying in Downing Street.
If the Conservatives won half a dozen or fewer Scottish seats they would
have barely the number needed to man the Scottish Office - unable to choose
who to field unless they drafted in MPs from England, which would be
unprecedented.
The outcome would be a further challenge to the legitimacy of the
Conservative party's rule in Scotland and increase the dissatisfaction of
many Scots with the Westminster system. In addition to Mr Lang losing his
seat in Galloway and Upper Nithsdale to the SNP, the Tories would lose two
other seats to the SNP. These are Perth and Kinross where the MP was Sir
Nicholas Fairbairn, and Tayside North where the MP was Mr Bill Walker.
In a hung parliament the SNP could come under pressure to do a deal with
Labour, a key element of which might be speedy implementation of Labour's
plans for devolved Scottish parliament.
While the SNP has totally ruled out deals with the Tories, it has been less
categorical with regard to Labour though it has said it will give 'no blank
cheques' to anyone.
A pale-looking Mr Sillars, having lost by about 4,000 votes, summed up the
situation, saying: 'Scotland has not yet resolved the paradox of what it
does when it votes Labour and England votes Tory.'
</TEXT>
