<HEADLINE>
FT  10 APR 92 / Election 1992: Nervous uncertainty hits Lib Dems
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PERHAPS it was the sweltering heat from the television lights, or perhaps it
was the sudden uncertainty about what the next few days could bring, but
there was a curious lack of celebration at the Liberal Democrats'
headquarters last night.
In a book-lined room high in the elegant building of the National Liberal
Club, almost within sight of Big Ben, party activists and journalists milled
around.
Party officials swallowed their disappointment at not gaining a larger share
of the vote, but seemed almost uneasy that that they may be about to take on
the role of power-brokers.
'We have achieved the objective of increasing our representation in what
could be a pivotal parliament,' said one official. He would not elaborate on
which way his party might be prepared to tip the balance.
Mr Des Wilson, campaign organiser - the strains of the campaign adding an
edge to his antipodean lilt - was equally reluctant to talk about
power-sharing, preferring to concentrate on his party's performance. 'It
would be very difficult for one party to go it alone with the present
figures,' he said. 'But I'd rather wait until tomorrow before saying any
more.'
'But I think you've got to see it in context. Only two years ago we had only
6 per cent in the opinion polls but tonight we've got about one-in-five
votes and at least 25 seats predicted. That's a real achievement.
'The challenge at one stage was to get through this election in what I can
call a state of survival, but in fact we have come through it very strongly
and could end up as the biggest third party presence since the war.'
He ascribed the Lib Dems' success to 'an extraordinarily happy campaign'.
Two decisions, he said, had contributed to the party's success. One was the
decision, taken two years ago, to run a positive campaign, stressing the
party's strengths, and to concentrate resources into campaigning in 40
crucial seats.
A hush fell as the results for Torbay - one of the target seats the Lib Dems
might just have gained - were announced. The hush continued as the news came
through that the Conservatives had held it. The atmosphere was broken by
booing as Mrs Margaret Thatcher appeared on screen. It was going to be a
long and nervous night.
Always the bridesmaid, but never the bride, said one observer. Last night,
the Lib Dems were coming to terms with the fact that they might just be a
very important bridesmaid indeed.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
