<HEADLINE>
FT  10 APR 92 / Election 1992: Close fight in three-way contest for TV
viewers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FOR THE first time in history the British people had a three-way choice of
election night coverage on television. After decades of two-way competition,
the BBC and ITV were joined by Sky News, Mr Rupert Murdoch's satellite
service, and early evidence suggested that Sky would hold its own pretty
impressively.
For the BBC, anchorman David Dimbleby sat on a railed podium at the centre
of a vast command room worthy of Dr Strangelove.
With a wave of the hand he called up electronic graphics, an army of
reporters, psephologists in the studio . . . and Peter Snow who had been
given not only an updated 'Swingometer' to play with, but a video version of
Downing Street.
At ITV, Peter's cousin, Jon Snow, anchored a programme which looked more
downbeat, but proved, as the earliest results came in, to be determined to
be first by hook or by crook. While the BBC audience was being told by ace
reporter Kate Adie how tremendously fast the bank clerks of Torbay were
counting the votes in order to be first in the race to declare, ITV went
live to Sunderland and showed their audience the first result before the BBC
even mentioned it.
More remarkable still, while the BBC cameras continued to show the scene at
Torbay, with no declaration being made, ITV flashed the result on the
screen. In previous elections the BBC has complained bitterly that ITV
announces results before returning officers make their declarations, and
here, sure enough, was clear proof.
The Sky service was a far more relaxed affair. David Frost chaired a panel
with Dennis Healey, Norman Tebbit, and David Owen, all of them now retired
from Westminster, but three of the greatest bruisers in studio politics over
many years. For the few able to monitor all three programmes simultaneously,
the Sky faces made a very tempting alternative to the whizzing around -
electronic and geographical - at the BBC and ITV. With the big turnout among
the electorate leading to long counts at town halls all over Britain, all
three television services dragged and viewers could be forgiven for musing
on the uncannily unchanging nature of these affairs in the UK.
At one moment the three programmes were showing the faces of Robin Day
(ITV), David Dimbleby (BBC) and David Frost (Sky): a trio which would have
been perfectly familiar to audiences in the early 1960s.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
</PAGE>
