<HEADLINE>
FT  10 APR 92 / Collectors beat dealers to Paris furniture: Saleroom
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NICHOLAS POWELL and ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE SALE in Paris this week of medieval and Renaissance furniture from the
collection of the French dealer Bruno Perrier, which many had predicted
would be a catastrophe, turned out to be the most successful sale of its
type for years.
Held by Jacques Tajan, the auction comprised 56 lots and made a total of
FFr21.45m (Pounds 2.22m). It also established a number of record prices.
Every leading dealer in Haute Epoque furniture attended the sale, only to be
outbid every time by private collectors who pushed most of the prices high
above estimate.
A New York collector acquired an exceptionally rare late 17th century
Piedmontese set of eight chairs, four armchairs and settee with well
preserved embroidered covers for FFr2.45m, above its FFr1m estimate. Bidding
for a 13th century oak cathedral chest with iron strapwork from Durham
tripled its estimate to reach FFr1.1m, establishing a record for English oak
furniture.
Competition for an oddly-shaped 16th century Lombard dignitary's chair in
walnut pushed the price up to FFr900,000, a record for a chair of the
period.
At the Drouot salerooms bids for the original 31-page handwritten pencil
manuscript of Maurice Ravel's Bolero of 1928 reached FFr1.8m. It was
pre-empted by the Bibliotheque Nationale.
Christie's sale of the Vung Tau cargo of 17th century Chinese blue and white
export porcelain in Amsterdam totalled Pounds 4.165m against an estimate of
Pounds 1.5m.
In London yesterday Christie's sold English furniture for Pounds 936,122,
with 18 per cent unsold. A complete set of 12 Irish George II embossed bird
pictures by Samuel Dixon, designed to be 'ornamental in lady's chambers',
doubled their estimate at Pounds 115,500.
At Sotheby's a Turner watercolour of Eyemouth in Berwickshire, commissioned
to illustrate Scott's novel 'The Bride of Lammermoor', sold for Pounds
77,000, just on target.
</TEXT>
