<HEADLINE>
FT  10 APR 92 / Blue Arrow judge steps down
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE JUDGE in the first Blue Arrow trial, who joined calls for a fundamental
review of the way complex fraud cases should be handled by the courts, is
stepping down, the Lord Chancellor's Department confirmed yesterday.
Mr Justice Brooke, another High Court judge, will take the place of Mr
Justice McKinnon, who presided over the year-long trial. Mr Justice Brooke
will preside over the two further Blue Arrow trials which are expected.
The department yesterday said that after a year running the first trial, Mr
Justice McKinnon deserved a break.
When the first trial ended in February with four convicted financial
advisers being given suspended sentences, Mr Justice McKinnon said the
lengthy proceedings had placed an unacceptable burden on all concerned.
Trial by jury in such cases would be threatened unless their presentation
was improved, he warned.
Mr Justice Brooke had a long record at the commercial Bar before being
appointed a judge, and was an inspector for the Department of Trade and
Industry during its investigation into House of Fraser, the stores group.
He will take over Blue Arrow on April 29th when the Serious Fraud Office
will ask him for proceedings against the remaining four defendants to be
split into two trials.
</TEXT>
