<HEADLINE>
FT  10 APR 92 / Policy shift signalled at CBI: Attitude of Davies to
political parties contrasts sharply with Banham stance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES LEADBEATER, Industrial Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Confederation of British Industry is set for a marked shift in its
approach to dealings with the government under Mr Howard Davies, the
controller of the Audit Commission, who will become the CBI's
director-general on July 1.
Mr Davies, whose appointment was approved yesterday by the CBI's governing
council, said he would prefer to work alongside policymakers whichever party
was in power, rather than 'throwing in ideas from the outside'.
He adopted a markedly less critical approach to Labour than either Sir John
Banham, the outgoing director-general, or Sir Brian Corby, the CBI president
who is to retire soon.
Mr Davies said there was an emerging consensus on economic management with
both Labour and the Conservative saying the right things about the economic
climate they wanted to create.
He said the CBI's task would be to work closely with the government to
influence the detail of policymaking from the inside in an attempt to make
sure legislation did not damage business interests.
Mr Davies indicated that while the CBI would be open about its policy
objectives, it would pursue them through detailed analysis of policy
proposals rather than engag-ing in wide-ranging public debate.
Mr Davies' style contrasts with that of Sir John, who has favoured a much
more public role, often outspokenly criticising government and opposition
policy.
Mr Davies' even-handed approach to the policy programmes of the two main
parties also contrasts with the stringent criticisms which Sir John and Sir
Brian have made of Labour party policy.
Early in the election campaign Sir Brian sent a letter to CBI members
reiterating what he saw as the gains that industry had made in the past
decade. It was widely seen as an endorsement for the Conservative party.
The CBI council called on the incoming government to maintain downward
pressure on inflation, to manage pressure for regional government and
devolution to minimise the damage it might do to business and to strengthen
considerably the Department of Trade and Industry.
The council called for the DTI to be refocused, with responsibility for the
National Economic Development Council transferred to it from the Treasury,
and its regulatory functions separated from its support for British
industry. It called for the DTI to take on the Department of Employment's
responsibilities for small businesses and enterprise.
</TEXT>
