<HEADLINE>
FT  10 APR 92 / Judgment on King's Cross overturned
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
ST BARTHOLOMEW'S Hosp-ital and the Church of England yesterday lost the
opportunity to make windfall profits of several million pounds from the
proposed Pounds 4.5bn redevelopment of land around London's King's Cross
station.
The Court of Appeal overturned a ruling by a High Court judge two years ago
that the hospital trustees and the Church commissioners had the right to buy
back from British Rail and National Carriers 52 acres of prime development
land at 1850s prices.
The land was compulsorily purchased to make way for rail lines. Bart's
surrendered 43 acres for which it was paid Pounds 53,250. The Church
commissioners sold nine acres, also under compulsory-purchase powers.
The land is part of the 125-acre site north of King's Cross station which
has been earmarked for development which includes the Channel tunnel
rail-link terminus, offices, shops, 1,350 new homes and a 35-acre park.
Under the ruling, Bart's and the Church commissioners could have purchased
the land at the original price of about Pounds 1,100 per acre and then sold
it at a large profit.
However, the Court of Appeal yesterday allowed an appeal brought by BR and
National Carriers. Lord Justice Stuart-Smith said he allowed the appeal
without regret. The hospital and the Church commissioners received the full
value of the land in the 1850s.
Bart's and the Church commissioners are to consider an appeal to the House
of Lords.
</TEXT>
