<HEADLINE>
FT  10 APR 92 / German employers reject arbitrators' pay proposal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PARKES and ANDREW FISHER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN, FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
GERMAN government hopes for a peaceful pay round and spending restraint
suffered a setback yesterday as employers rejected an arbitration proposal
for a 5.4 per cent wage rise for west Germany's 3m public sector workers.
Mr Rudolf Seiters, the interior minister responsible for federal and local
government wage policy, was joined by private sector employers and other
government politicians in a chorus of protest. 'The arbitrators' suggestion
fails to take account of current economic conditions and therefore cannot be
a basis for agreement,' Mr Seiters said.
Mr Hermann-Otto Solms, leader of the Free Democrat parliamentary group, said
the offer was not acceptable. It would cost federal and state budgets an
additional DM20bn (Pounds 7bn) a year, he claimed.
The non-binding proposal, put forward after a 7-6 vote in favour, included
extra payments totalling DM750 a head. The employers' final offer in the
six-day conciliation talks consisted of 5 per cent from April plus DM400
back-pay.
'Anyone who thinks that is too little must go on strike,' said Mr Friedrich
Zimmermann, the employer-nominated negotiator.
Officials of the OTV and DAG unions, which represent most of the workforce,
said if the employers did not improve their offer when formal negotiations
resumed on Monday, they would hold strike ballots.
The last public sector strike, in 1974, stopped virtually all public
services for three days.
The overall 'compromise' package for the public sector is lower than the
6.34 per cent steelworkers' award, agreed earlier this year, but similar to
the 5.8 per cent deal offered to bank staff last weekend by employers which
enjoyed record profits last year.
Engineering employers negotiating with unions over a 9.5 per cent claim,
said yesterday the offer was too high. Economic recovery in east Germany
could be held up considerably if Bonn plays too interventionist a role in
the region's industry, the Bundesbank warns in its annual report published
yesterday, reports Andrew Fisher from Frankfurt.
The central bank also repeats its concern that the value of the D-Mark as
well as German economic growth and employment were at risk from inflation
and the weak state of foreign economies.
The bank made clear it had no intention yet of relaxing monetary policy.
</TEXT>
