<HEADLINE>
FT  10 APR 92 / Row over Black Sea fleet is resolved
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRYSTIA FREELAND
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SEVASTOPOL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
UKRAINE and Russia averted a clash over the Black Sea fleet yesterday by
suspending their claims to the former Soviet Union's naval force.
The compromise was negotiated by telephone between Ukrainian President
Leonid Kravchuk and Mr Boris Yeltsin, his Russian counterpart.
It followed a day of tension in Sevastopol, the fleet's headquarters in the
Crimea. Admiral Igor Kasatonov, the fleet's commander, revealed that he had
deployed armoured personnel carriers to patrol the streets following rumours
of a Ukrainian attack.
The seamen are mostly Ukrainian while the officers are mainly Russian.
Crimea itself was once part of Russia and is now a district of Ukraine.
Conflict over the fleet has marked a low point in increasingly hostile
relations between Ukraine and Russia, the two most powerful members of the
Commonwealth of Independent States. Ukraine had threatened to leave the CIS
over the issue.
The row has caused anxiety among western leaders concerned about the former
Soviet Union's nuclear weapons. In Brussels yesterday, Nato told Moscow and
Kiev of 'serious allied concerns' about Ukraine's decision to suspend the
transfer of tactical nuclear weapons to Russia.
Ukrainian authorities and the commander of the fleet announced the agreement
on the Black Sea fleet yesterday. A commission will be set up to negotiate
the division of the fleet between the two Slavic giants.
The fleet is strategically important because of its nuclear capacity and
because of its access to the Mediterranean and the Middle East.
It was traditionally, in the former Soviet Union, a counterbalance to the US
Sixth Fleet in the Mediterranean.
Only 1 per cent of Black Sea fleet sailors had sworn an oath of allegiance
to Ukraine, according to the admiral. But Mr Dmytro Pavlychko, a member of
the Ukrainian negotiating team, said 70 per cent of sailors would like to
swear allegiance to Ukraine.
Symbols were at the heart of the compromise between the two states. Admiral
Kasatonov confirmed that Mr Yeltsin's order to hoist the Russian tricolour
over the ships of the Black Sea fleet had been suspended. The fleet still
flies the old Soviet naval flag, which Admiral Kasatonov acknowledged was
inappropriate since the Soviet Union no longer existed.
</TEXT>
