FT  10 APR 92 / International Company News: PWA seeks CDollars 200m in
airline deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GIBBENS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MONTREAL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PWA, the parent of Canadian Airlines International, is seeking CDollars 200m
(USDollars 169.5m) cash in return for selling 25 per cent of the airline to
American Airlines.
Mr Rhys Eyton, chairman of PWA and the airline, said in Toronto that
effective control of Canadian Airlines would remain in Canada, in spite of
pooling of computer resources and ground personnel.
He was confident AMR, parent of American, was ready 'to consider an equity
infusion of more than CDollars 200m to Canadian Airlines in exchange for the
25 per cent interest and the right to provide management services'.
Analysts had estimated Mr Eyton would seek about CDollars 100m in new equity
for Canadian. Both companies are now in negotiations.
Mr Eyton said PWA's common shareholders would be favourably affected because
it would be Canadian Airlines issuing new Treasury shares to American in
return for the cash infusion and 'a comprehensive strategic alliance'.
'We cannot be absolutely sure the deal with American will be finalised, and
that is why we're negotiating with our lenders to double our operating
credit lines to CDollars 400m,' said Mr Eyton.
He estimated that between 1,500 and 2,000 ground workers would lose their
jobs, but there would be no impact on pilots, flight attendants, counter
staff, and the maintenance base in Vancouver.
</TEXT>
