<HEADLINE>
FT  10 APR 92 / UK Company News: Whatman knocked by US recession
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE US recession was blamed by Whatman, the specialist paper and filtration
equipment maker, for a 16 per cent fall, from Pounds 11m to Pounds 9.2m, in
pre-tax profits for the year to December 31.
More than 60 per cent of the group's Pounds 49.6m (Pounds 44.6m) turnover is
US-based. The UK accounts for just 17 per cent with the rest in continental
Europe and the Far East.
A strong performance from miro-filtration products in North America shielded
the group from the worst effects of the US downturn.
Mr Hugh Perrott, finance director, said: 'A worst economic background than
we had experienced was partly offset by gains from our new focused products
where we had increased investment.'
Reorganisation costs of Pounds 300,000, relating to the discontinuation of
manufacturing filter systems, was taken above the line.
A net interest charge of Pounds 378,000, compared with net interest income
of Pounds 733,000, mainly due to tax increases in Japan and the US. Earnings
per share fell from 33.1p to 26.6p.
While capital expenditure fell from Pounds 10m to Pounds 4.7m, marketing and
product development expenditure is expected to rise as a proportion of sales
over the current year.
The final dividend is increased to 5.8p making a total of 8.7p compared with
7.75p. Mr Perrott said the group aimed to increase the dividend steadily.
</TEXT>
