<HEADLINE>
FT  10 APR 92 / O&amp;Y poised to replace Johnson
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON and ROBERT PESTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
OLYMPIA &amp; York Developments, the financially stretched Canadian property
group, is close to appointing a senior businessman to replace Mr Tom Johnson
as president.
Earlier this week, O&amp;Y was contemplating leaving the post of president empty
after Mr Johnson's imminent departure, so that Mr Paul Reichmann, O&amp;Y's
founder, would be in complete control.
However, yesterday it emerged a replacement is likely.
Mr Johnson, the senior banker brought in as president only two weeks ago,
returned to his home in New Jersey on Friday. He is in talks with O&amp;Y over
whether he will have a continuing role at the company and whether he should
be compensated for loss of office.
Sources close to the negotiations between Mr Johnson and O&amp;Y said the rift
between the two stemmed in part from a disagreement over the terms of Mr
Johnson's contract, including how much and when he should be paid.
Mr Steve Miller, a partner in James D Wolfensohn, the US investment bank, is
expected to replace Mr Johnson as chairman of O&amp;Y's planning and finance
committee, which is drafting the plan to restructure O&amp;Y's debt of more than
Dollars 20bn. Mr Miller has been taking the lead in formulating the
reconstruction plan.
Meanwhile, it was reported yesterday that Mr Li Ka-Shing, the Hong Kong
magnate, will be in Toronto next Tuesday for talks with O&amp;Y and its bankers.
Mr Li, who forged a partnership with O&amp;Y late last year in a New York office
building, has expressed interest in buying some of the assets likely to be
put up for sale.
Besides property holdings, these include controlling interests in several
large Canadian natural resource companies.
An O&amp;Y spokesman said yesterday a separate meeting with representatives of
about 100 of the company's bank lenders was scheduled to go ahead amid
strict security in Toronto's Sheraton Centre on Monday. Between 200 to 300
people are expected to attend the meeting.
Mr Johnson, who was formerly president of Manufacturers Hanover, was brought
into O&amp;Y at the suggestion of the company's main lenders to support the two
Reichmann brothers, Paul and Albert.
</TEXT>
