<HEADLINE>
FT  10 APR 92 / Move to block private Marchioness action
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
AN ATTEMPT to block a private prosecution over the Marchioness pleasure-boat
disaster on the Thames, in which 51 people died, began in the High Court
yesterday.
Last November a London magistrate gave the go-ahead for committal
proceedings on a manslaughter charge against South Coast Shipping Company,
owner of the dredger Bowbelle, the other vessel involved in the collision,
and four senior managers, brought by Mr Ivor Glogg, whose wife died in the
accident.
Yesterday South Coast Shipping Company and Mr Peter Butcher, operations
manager, Mr Brian Darwell, marine manager, Mr Edward Greenwood, company
superintendent, and Mr Robert Samuel, general manager, asked two judges to
quash the magistrate's decision.
The tragedy occurred in the early hours of August 21 1989 when the
Marchioness, on which a party was being held, collided with the dredger.
Sir David Hopkin, the chief stipendiary magistrate, ruled that Mr Glogg had
the legal standing necessary to give him the right to bring a private
prosecution.
The defendants argue that Mr Glogg lacks sufficient legal standing; that the
private prosecution is 'a misuse or manipulation of the process of the
court' which amounts to an abuse; that the case is not a genuine prosecution
but a means of conducting a public inquiry and airing grievances; and that
delay and publicity have led to unfairness.
</TEXT>
