<HEADLINE>
FT  10 APR 92 / Firms make plans for summer lull in work
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ACCOUNTANCY firms are gearing up for a substantial lull in work during the
summer with a variety of tactics to keep their employees occupied.
Some are placing extra emphasis on staff taking all their holidays during
the late summer, when the volume of audit work is traditionally lowest.
Others are seconding them to other departments or giving them projects for
their firms' internal use.
Managers have been pincered by two effects of the recession: a decline in
some areas of business activity, and - because there are fewer jobs
elsewhere - reluctance by younger staff to leave.
With most companies' financial year-ends in December and March, audit staff
will be kept busy into June. Many of the more junior accountants are likely
to be at a loose end for the subsequent three or four months.
Mr Paul Woodrow, public relations manager at Robson Rhodes, said: 'There has
been a vacuum in work for auditors during the summer since Noah was a boy.'
But he agreed that some areas of work had been lower this year than in the
past.
Mr Richard Owen, national director of personnel at Touche Ross, said that
while audit work might be heading for a lull, insolvency work was 'insanely
busy'.
KPMG Peat Marwick took what the firm describes as 'the most definitive
solution' to the problem of spare capacity last month when it made more than
300 audit staff redundant.
Meanwhile Price Waterhouse has given senior personnel discretion to allow
their staff to take unpaid leave, lifting a rule that no employee can take
more than two weeks a year of unpaid leave in lieu of overtime.
Other firms point out that the late summer is the period when students
should be spending the most time training and studying for their accountancy
exams.
</TEXT>
