<HEADLINE>
FT  10 APR 92 / Late surge in support for Tories cheers investors
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SHARES, government gilt-edged securities and sterling all rose sharply
yesterday in London, as investors were cheered by opinion polls indicating a
last-minute surge in support for the Conservative party.
As voting took place in the general election, financial markets reasoned
that a Tory defeat was not a foregone conclusion, in spite of the polls
which have pointed either to a Labour victory or a hung parliament for most
of the campaign.
However, trading in most markets was thin. This was indicative of the
extreme caution about efforts to predict the outcome of the election.
Many investors are braced for considerable volatility when the markets
reopen today.
On the London stock market, the FT-SE 100 index of leading shares rose by
43.2 to close at 2,436.4, while gilts saw a half-point gain.
On currency markets, investors bought the pound in place of the D-Mark and
other units, on the basis that whichever government is elected is unlikely
to opt for a sterling devaluation.
The support pushed up sterling by 1 1/2 pfennigs to a London close of
DM2.8575.
Sterling also rose nearly 2 cents against the dollar, to Dollars 1.7665.
During the campaign, markets have generally expressed negative sentiments
about the possibility of a Tory defeat. However, after a 65-point fall in
the FT-SE index last week, the index has recovered 54 points in the past
four days.
Meanwhile, sterling has climbed this week by more than 2 pfennigs,
depressing expectations that a new government might be faced by a run on the
pound which could force up base rates, now 10.5 per cent.
Reflecting the more sanguine view in the money markets about such a
possibility, the three-month interbank rate was quoted last night at about
10 3/4 per cent, down about one-eighth of a percentage point. Last week, the
three-month rate, at which banks lend among themselves, had climbed to about
11 1/2 per cent, signalling that many investors thought a base-rate rise was
imminent.
Lex, Page 20
Government bonds, Page 30
Currencies, Page 33
London stocks, Page 42
</TEXT>
