<HEADLINE>
FT  09 APR 92 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow falls for second day in
nervous trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN ZAGOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   New York
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
CONTINUED weakness in Japanese stocks, concern that US equities are
over-priced, and another wave of index-related program selling pushed Wall
Street sharply lower for the second day, writes Karen Zagor in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average, after dropping as low as 3,163.47 in the
morning, closed 32.20 down on balance at 3,181.35 for a two-day plunge of 94
points. Total New York SE volume was a heavy 249.3m shares. Declining issues
led advances by 1,392 to 409 on the big board. The Dow's lowest close of the
year was 3,172.41 on January 2.
The falls were less dramatic in other market indices, which analysts said
had started to correct ahead of the Dow. The Standard &amp; Poor's 500 was 3.56
off at 394.50, while the Nasdaq composite lost 7.93 to 573.68.
Bank issues were particularly hard hit by the erosion in their Japanese
counterparts. Rumours that a Japanese bank had failed to make a payment on a
swap contract swept through the market in the morning, prompting Bankers
Trust to deny rumours that it had taken a large loss from the failure of a
swap transaction.
JP Morgan and Bankers Trust dipped Dollars 1 1/2 to Dollars 52 3/8 and
Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 51 3/8 respectively. BankAmerica shed Dollars 1 1/8
to Dollars 38 7/8 but Citicorp edged forward Dollars  1/4 to Dollars 15 1/4
.
IBM was one of the few blue chips to buck the trend yesterday, adding
Dollars 2 1/2 at Dollars 84 7/8 . The improvement was attributed to a higher
rating of the stock by Merrill Lynch.
Blue chips falling in active trading included AT&amp;T, off Dollars 1 1/8 at
Dollars 40 7/8 , and General Electric, down Dollars 1 1/4 at Dollars 72 7/8
.
Wal-Mart continued to see active trading following the death of the
company's founder earlier this week. The stock, which had moved higher
immediately after the news of the death of Mr Sam Walton, lost Dollars 1/4
yesterday to Dollars 51 3/8 .
Among big retailers, Sears rose Dollars  1/4 to Dollars 44 5/8 , Woolworth
improved Dollars  1/8 to Dollars 29 and The Limited slipped Dollars  5/8 to
Dollars 26 1/8 .
In the over-the-counter market, Apple Computer lost Dollars 1 3/8 to Dollars
55 7/8 but Microsoft improved Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 117 1/4 .
Teledyne plunged Dollars 4 5/8 to Dollars 22 3/4 after the electronics
equipment company posted first-quarter operating profits of 21 cents a
share, compared with 28 cents a year earlier.
Primerica, which owns Smith Barney Harris Upham, fell Dollars 1 1/8 to
Dollars 37 on fears that the securities sector may not be able to maintain
its record earnings.
Canada
TORONTO continued its downward trend but ended above the day's worst. The
composite index lost 18.5 to 3,318.1, after Tuesday's 49-point drop. The
index touched 3,299.1 at its low for the day. Falls outscored gains by 443
to 152 after volume of 27.4m shares.
Traders said the market is nervously looking ahead to the US producer and
consumer price indices for March due today and tomorrow respectively.
Depending on the figures, the market could see the US Federal Reserve ease
its monetary policy.
Power Corp dipped CDollars  1/4 to CDollars 14 1/2 after the company
reported slightly lower fourth-quarter earnings. Power Financial gave up
CDollars  7/8 to CDollars 19 1/4 after announcing higher fourth-quarter
earnings.
Alberta Energy, up CDollars  1/4 at CDollars 10 1/4 , increased its annual
dividend to 35 cents a share from 33 cents.
