FT  09 APR 92 / Government Bonds: Gilts rally as dealers cover short
positions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TRACY CORRIGAN and KAREN ZAGOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
GILT prices rallied  3/8 point as dealers rushed to cover short positions
ahead of today's general election. The market was boosted by buying interest
from foreign investors, suggesting that fears about sterling weakness may be
subsiding.
Many dealers have been running short positions ahead of the election, and so
were caught short of bonds by the rally. However, some traders have been
flattening their positions on the grounds that a Labour victory in the
election has been largely discounted.
The short end led the way, with the short sterling future on Liffe up 1/4
point, suggesting that fears of interest rate rises after the election may
be subsiding. The market was also boosted by rumours of a new poll showing
the Tories three points ahead of Labour.
The short end of the market outperformed long-dated government bonds in
France and Germany, in choppy trading conditions. French and German 10-year
government bond future contracts failed to break through key resistance
levels, and dealers reported some profit-taking.
The OAT future on the Matif, the French futures exchange, ended down 0.10
point at 107.90, while the Bund future on Liffe in London closed a touch
lower at 87.90.
A speech by France's new prime minister, Mr Pierre Beregovoy, underlining a
stronger emphasis on economic growth, had been largely discounted by the
market, according to dealers. Improved retail demand for short-dated paper
should help the market absorb this month's auction of two- and five-year
bonds, dealers added.
US Treasury prices edged lower yesterday on the back of the Treasury's
seven-year note auction and a sharp drop in the US equity market.
In late trading, the bellwether 30-year bond was  7/16 lower at 1001 7/8 ,
yielding 7.92 per cent, while the two-year note slid  1/32 to yield 5.28 per
cent
The Federal Reserve refrained from intervening in the open market, and in
late trading Fed funds were changing hands at 3 3/4 per cent.
Trading was dominated by the poor results of the afternoon's auction of
Dollars 9.75bn in seven-year notes. Players were unsettled by the 1.93 per
cent bid;cover ratio and the average yield of 7.11 per cent with a
three-point tail.
The short end received some support from renewed speculation that weak money
supply growth and a sluggish recovery might prompt the Fed to ease monetary
policy.
IN the German market, the yield curve steepened further, as the Euromark
contract rallied by  1/8 point. Dealers said the view that inflation had
peaked and an interest cut may come sooner than had been thought, helped
buoy the short end. There were further rumours, again denied, of a public
sector wage settlement.
JAPANESE government bond prices stabilised, helped by the stock market,
which ended off its lows. The market remained nervous, though, with rumours
of further problems in the banking sector.
However, there was also some speculation that the Bank of Japan may speed up
the process of easing interest rates.
</TEXT>
