FT  09 APR 92 / International Capital Markets: NEC forms chip alliance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   Tokyo
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
NEC, the Japanese electronics company, and MIPS Computer Systems, the US
microprocessor manufacturer, have agreed to develop jointly a 64-bit Risc
(reduced instruction set computing) chip for a wide range of uses, Reuter
reports from Tokyo.
Risc chips, which process information faster than conventional
microprocessors because they have fewer instructions in a computer
operation, are mostly used in workstations.
Under the agreement, MIPS will design VRX chips according to NEC's
specifications, and NEC will get exclusive manufacturing and marketing
rights for the first year. NEC said it hopes to launch VRX products in the
latter half of 1993.
The new chip will be modelled on the MIPS R4000 central processing unit.
