<HEADLINE>
FT  09 APR 92 / International Company News: Iberia plans Pta760bn
investments
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   Madrid
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
IBERIA Airlines would invest Pta760bn (Dollars 7.35bn) between now and 1996
to carry out medium-term strategic plans, chairman Mr Miguel Aguilo, said
yesterday, Reuter reports from Madrid.
He told a government committee the plan foresaw an average annual revenue
rise of 13.7 per cent between 1992 and 1996, and a 9.5 per cent rise in
costs. This should mean profits of about Pta4.9bn in 1992, rising to
Pta55.9bn in 1996.
He said 51 per cent of the investments would come from internal cash-flow,
33 per cent from bank debt, and 16 per cent from the company's
recently-authorised Pta120bn capital increase.
The state airline's financial costs are projected at Pta23bn a year until
1996, with total debt rising from Pta240bn at the end of 1992 to Pta345bn at
the end of the period.
Mr Aguilo said Iberia was not seeking alliances with European airlines.
'Alliances with European partners are not envisaged for now as our main
priority is the strategic plan,' he said.
He said the plan involved a greater international profile, improved service
and a stronger role in European, Latin American and east Asian markets.
Mr Aguilo said Iberia's fleet would incorporate 130 new aircraft between
1989 and 1996, and that 50 others would be retired from service during this
period.
Spain's new high-velocity train (AVE) and development of the country's road
network threatened Iberia, he said. Domestic traffic was expected to grow by
only 7.7 per cent, against a European average of 11.7 per cent, between 1992
and 1996.
Mr Aguilo said Iberia had not yet signed contracts to build its own terminal
at Barajas airport in Madrid. Nor had it decided whether to sell its
headquarters in the centre of the capital.
Iberia made a group pre-tax loss of Pta51.32bn in 1991, after Pta26.11bn the
previous year.
</TEXT>
