<HEADLINE>
FT  09 APR 92 / International Company News: US bid to restore Stempel's
credibility
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE BOARD of General Motors, which this week announced a large executive
shake-up, yesterday sought to shore up the battered credibility of Mr Robert
Stempel, the company's chairman, with a declaration that non-executive
directors did not intend to interfere in his day-to-day running of the
business.
A board meeting on Monday demoted Mr Stempel's long-time lieutenant, Mr
Lloyd Reuss, and also appeared to clip the chairman's wings when it
announced that Mr John Smale, a non-executive director, would take over Mr
Stempel's leadership of the board's executive committee.
This was generally interpreted as a rebuke to Mr Stempel, since the
committee has enjoyed the power to run General Motors between regular board
meetings.
However, the company yesterday belatedly explained that the executive
committee had never actually met, and its function had been changed at
Monday's meeting: it was no longer authorised to act on behalf of the full
board but now had the role of advising the chairman. The aim was to make
communication between the board and the chairman quicker and more effective.
Explaining Mr Stempel's replacement by Mr Smale, a company spokesman said:
'The chairman could not be the chairman of a committee that is meant to
advise him.'
Mr Smale, who played a leading behind-the-scenes role in encouraging
Monday's shake-up, himself issued a brief statement saying that outside
directors did not 'intend to involve ourselves in the day-to-day business of
GM.
'That job is the responsibility of Bob Stempel and he has the board's full
support and confidence in pursuing the goal to accelerate the return to
profitability of GM's North American operations.'
Despite these explanations, Wall Street observers said the new
responsibilities of the executive committee, together with the staff
changes, underlined the concern of non-executive directors at the pace of
change within the company, and their determination to get a more rapid and
thorough flow of information on developing events.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 28
