<HEADLINE>
FT  09 APR 92 / International Company News: Chevron freezes pay levels
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN ZAGOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CHEVRON, one of the biggest US oil and gas groups, yesterday said it had
frozen the pay of Mr Kenneth Derr, chairman and chief executive, and other
officers and personnel as part of the company's cost-cutting programme.
Mr Derr said the pay freeze, at 1991 levels, took effect on April 1 and
would remain for at least three months. In addition, bonuses tied to
Chevron's annual performance were significantly lower.
Chevron, which had a difficult fourth quarter, said it would cut capital and
exploratory spending by 11 per cent this year to Dollars 4.7bn.
Cost-cutting is expected to reduce operating expenses by at least Dollars
600m by the third quarter of 1993.
In addition, Chevron is shifting the focus of its upstream activities
overseas.
'The oil business is mostly moving overseas, partly by choice, but mostly
because we have no choice,' said Mr Derr. 'High potential areas for finding
new reserves are now off-limits to us.'
Mr Derr said the company expected to raise as much as Dollars 700m from the
sale of existing oil and gas fields in the US.
On Wall Street, shares in Chevron fell Dollars  3/8 to Dollars 64 7/8 in a
declining market.
</TEXT>
