<DOCNO>FT922-13796</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CDIBOAFVFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920409
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  09 APR 92 / Tension rises over Iraqi missiles
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARK NICHOLSON and GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN and the US voiced alarm yesterday that the Baghdad regime had moved
anti-aircraft missiles into a northern Iraqi exclusion zone, posing a threat
to western military aircraft patrolling the area.
The US said Iraqi ground forces had also moved closer to Kurdish settlements
in the area, raising fears of military action against the Kurds.
The rising tension in northern Iraq has revived the possibility of a strike
by the US and its allies against Iraqi forces. General Colin Powell,
chairman of the US joint chiefs of staff, refused to rule out this option in
London yesterday after talks with Mr John Major, UK prime minister.
Allied aircraft in the region are understood to be on a state of alert. The
Iraqi missiles' radars have been tracking US, British and French aircraft,
based in Turkey, and the US has informally warned Iraqi commanders that any
attempt to lock missiles on to allied flights would be viewed as a hostile
act. The US state department was last night preparing a formal warning.
Allied officials said the Soviet-made SAM-2 and SAM-3 missile batteries were
moved within the last 10 days to Mosul, 32km north of the 36th parallel.
After the Gulf war, Britain and the US ordered Iraq not to stage military
operations against the Kurds north of this parallel on pain of possible
allied counter-attack.
Admiral David Jeremiah, vice-chairman of the US joint chiefs of staff, said
in Washington the allied powers were concerned about Iraq's motives in
deploying the anti-aircraft missiles in the protected area.
'We view the presence of these systems with considerable concern because
surface-to-air missiles have no purpose other than to be used against
aircraft, and the only aircraft flying in that area are allied,' he said.
The movement of missiles follows reports of renewed attacks by Iraqi forces
on the southern fringe of Kurdish held areas in the north and signs of a
build-up of Iraqi armour in the region.
Iraqi opposition groups in London also claim an Iraqi force last week
launched a three-day offensive against Shias in the country's southern
marshes.
These skirmishes and the missile deployment have intensified Anglo-US
consultations on a possible punitive raid to deter Iraq from threatening the
Kurds - or from testing too far the resolve of the Gulf war allies in their
undertaking to protect them.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 22
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-13797</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CDIBOAFUFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920409
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  09 APR 92 / Beregovoy puts employment first: Opposition clamour over
party financing interrupts new premier's speech
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN DAVIDSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Pierre Beregovoy, France's new prime minister, yesterday undertook to
make the fight against unemployment the first priority of his government,
but without undermining the existing policy of economic rigour and monetary
stability.
His opening declaration to the National Assembly, however, was subjected to
a systematic barrage of hostile clamour from the conservative opposition
benches, indicating that the new government is likely to face a rough ride
in the 11 months left before the next general election.
Mr Beregovoy lived up to his reputation for straight dealing when he
announced that there would be no change in France's electoral system before
those elections.
Last autumn President Francois Mitterrand urged a shift towards more
proportional representation, which set off a ferment of suspicion that he
intended to change the voting rules to evade defeat. That way out has now
been closed, in a demonstration of the new premier's authority.
The crescendo in the uproar came when Mr Beregovoy undertook to wage war
against corruption in public life. Scandals concerning illegal party
financing have in recent years tarnished the reputation of the French
political establishment, especially the Socialist party, and Mr Beregovoy
promised his government would give full support to judicial investigations.
He said: 'If there are cases which have been delayed, believe me, they will
not be delayed any more.'
At this point, his speech was effectively drowned out by opposition
barracking. Mr Beregovoy then ominously waved a piece of paper which, he
said, contained 'a list of persons about whom I might want to speak to you'.
After even louder roars of protest, about a quarter of the opposition
members walked out. When they had gone, Mr Beregovoy said that none of the
names on his list was a member of the National Assembly.
To accelerate the recovery, Mr Beregovoy said value added tax applied to
cars and luxury goods at a higher rate of 22 per cent would be reduced to
the standard rate of 18.6 per cent from next Monday, nine months ahead of
the timing set by the European Community's single market.
The finance ministry indicated that the VAT cut would cost FFr4.3bn (Pounds
448m) in 1992 and FFr7bn in a full year. But Mr Beregovoy made clear his
government intended to maintain a firm grip to control the budget deficit.
He promised that by the end of October 900,000 of the long-term unemployed,
out of a total figure just short of 3m, would be offered either a job, or
training, or a suitable form of community service. In addition, he said the
government would promote part-time working, in part by reducing social
security charges.
He promised that any new spending in the fight against unemployment would be
financed either by the sale of state assets or by cost savings.
As a gesture of support for nuclear disarmament, meanwhile, finally Mr
Beregovoy announced that France would suspend all nuclear weapon tests for
the rest of this year.
</TEXT>
