FT  09 APR 92 / IBM opens 'office of the future'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Nick Temple, IBM's UK chief executive, today opens the company's first
building in the UK to implement fully its 'office of the future' concept.
Many staff will have no desks.
Half the 120 employees at the IBM North East England regional headquarters
in Newcastle upon Tyne have been equipped with laptop computers and mobile
telephones so they no longer need to travel to the office every day.
The staff, who work in sales, client support, servicing and engineering, use
the equipment to communicate by telephone from their homes and cars or their
clients' offices with IBM's computer network, accessing information and
messages.
The concept, dubbed Smart - Space, Morale and Remote Technology - by IBM,
has been partly introduced by the company at its London and Glasgow offices,
but Newcastle, where employees have just moved from old premises to new
accommodation, is the first to switch entirely to the concept for all field
staff.
Mr Peter Austin, Newcastle location manager, said the staff response had
been enthusiastic. It allowed them to work more flexibly, with greater
control over their hours.
