FT  09 APR 92 / Transport union urges stricter sea safety law
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE RMT transport union yesterday urged the government to break ranks with
the world community and introduce tougher legislation on sea safety.
Mr Tony McGregor, RMT assistant general secretary with responsibility for
shipping, said: 'British seafarers should not have to wait for the world to
agree safety standards. Our members' lives are at risk while other countries
prevaricate.'
The statement follows remarks made at a meeting in London of the
International Maritime Organisation, the UN agency that draws up sea safety
standards. The organisation emphasises the need for states to act
unanimously and warns of chaos resulting from different national standards.
The procedure is slow. Safety standards for new roll-on roll-off ships, of
the same type of the Herald of Free Enterprise, came into force three years
years after the 1987 disaster which claimed almost 200 lives.
Mr William O'Neil, secretary-general of the organisation, said: 'Despite the
efforts of some states, the number of sub-standard ships sailing the ocean
is too high and the loss of life is unacceptable.' Mr O'Neil said world
shipping was facing enormous challenges in ageing fleets, higher replacement
costs, poor safety standards and a shortage of manpower.
All sections of the industry had to work to ensure that high safety
standards were achieved, he said.
Any compromise 'must provide a level of safety that is acceptable to the
entire shipping world.'
Earlier in the week he said: 'Unilateral action on the part of any
government gives us all cause for concern. However, it would be wrong for
this organisation to express such concern if it does not at the same time
make a concerted effort to adopt standards which are both realistic and
highly regarded.'
He said human error was the principal cause of shipping casualties. Action
on training and certification standards for seafarers were a high priority.
</TEXT>
