<HEADLINE>
FT  09 APR 92 / Retraining palates on the Continent:  A traditional British
Rail breakfast served on the Paris to Brussels express
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD EVANS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INTERCITY, the British Rail flagship, contributed to entente cordiale this
week by serving up bacon and black pudding on the Paris to Brussels
early-morning express.
Bemused Continental travellers have had their croissants and coffee
supplemented by BR's 'Great British Breakfast' as part of an InterCity
campaign to dispel its reputation for not-so-haute cuisine.
In a week-long experiment, eight InterCity executives, chefs and
stewardesses are serving a choice of full British breakfasts on the 7.05am
express from Paris, and an evening meal on the return.
The initial signs are good. Out of 150 customers in three crowded dining
cars yesterday, 70 per cent opted for the Great British Breakfast rather
than the meagre local alternative. A big majority chose the full works of
bacon, sausage, tomatoes, mushrooms, fried potatoes and black pudding, with
a few opting for smoked salmon and scrambled eggs. One opted for kippers,
but he turned out to be English.
Reactions were favourable, although some customers were more intrigued by
the activities of the BBC television crew and the half-dozen journalists
flown by InterCity from London to witness the historic event, than by the
food. One Parisian lawyer said he thoroughly approved of the Great British
Breakfast, but wasn't sure he could cope with it every day.
On the evening journey there is pheasant pate with Cumberland sauce and a
choice of grilled salmon with a lobster butter sauce or noisettes of Welsh
lamb with a redcurrant sauce, a dish created and prepared by Mr Brian
Challis, InterCity's chef of the year. There is a selection of British
cheeses, including ripe Stilton, summer pudding, and an aperitif of
sparkling wine from Kent.
UK travellers will have the opportunity to enjoy some Continental catering
when a team from Wagons Lits offers its menus on BR later this year. There
could be further habit-changing swaps if the experiment is successful.
Mr Terry Coyle, InterCity's director of on-board services, said: 'InterCity
catering is the envy of most European train operators . . . we would not be
doing this if we thought it would not be totally successful. French trains
have nothing like the Great British Breakfast.'
</TEXT>
