<HEADLINE>
FT  09 APR 92 / Election 1992: Union links set to survive
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
STATE FUNDING for political parties, promised in Labour's manifesto, would
loosen but not sever the ties between the party and the unions that finance
it, according to Labour and union officials.
Both sides agree that a more distant relationship is preferable. State
funding would be a financial relief for the Labour-affiliated unions, which
at present finance about half Labour's running costs between elections and
nearly all election spending.
Mr John Edmonds, leader of the GMB general union, believes his proposal for
reducing the union block vote at Labour conference from 90 per cent to 50
per cent is likely to be accepted more quickly as a result of the prospect
of state funding.
Labour officials argue that the unions' 'political ballast' at party
conference and in the electoral college will still be required to balance
the unreliable constituency parties.
</TEXT>
