<HEADLINE>
FT  09 APR 92 / New York victory puts Clinton within reach of nomination as
Brown falters
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   Washington
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR BILL Clinton left New York yesterday, after two gruelling weeks of
campaigning, with the Democratic party's presidential nomination firmly in
his reach, reports George Graham in Washington.
By winning the New York primary on Tuesday with 41 per cent of the vote, the
Arkansas governor vaulted the biggest hurdle of his campaign for the
nomination.
Victories in Wisconsin and Kansas on the same day added to his commanding
lead over both Mr Jerry Brown, former governor of California and the only
major candidate still in the Democratic race, and Mr Paul Tsongas, former
senator from Massachusetts, who continues to win votes although he has
formally withdrawn from the race.
President George Bush, meanwhile, continued to record comfortable victories
in Republican party primaries.
Mr Clinton acknowledged yesterday that many voters still felt uncomfortable
with him because of the series of allegations about adultery, marijuana
smoking and draft dodging that have beset his campaign. 'I'm not interested
in whether they love me or not. I want them to respect me and want me to be
their president,' he said.
Although Mr Tsongas caused a surprise by winning 29 per cent of the New York
vote, he said he would take several days to decide whether to re-enter the
race.
Most politicians in Washington believe that, even if Mr Tsongas decides to
relaunch his candidacy, he will do so with a severely limited campaigning
schedule, more in the hope of influencing his party's policies than of
winning the nomination.
Mr Brown, however, vowed to soldier on, despite having been largely
repudiated by voters in New York, where he won only 25 per cent of the vote.
He fared better in Wisconsin, with 35 per cent.
Clinton supporters were working intensely yesterday to win over the 772
Democratic party committee members and Congress members who will take part
in the nominating convention in July as unelected super-delegates.
Mr Clinton is estimated to have the backing of 213 of them already, as well
as that of 50 per cent of the 2,197 delegates so far committed by primaries
and caucuses.
Although Mr Clinton is unlikely to be able to clinch the nomination
mathematically until the last round of state primaries on June 2, his
supporters believe Congressional leaders will now quickly fall in behind his
candidacy.
'We just got through the biggest obstacle which was New York. From here on,
Jerry Brown is a mathematical impossibility and Paul Tsongas is
mathematically improbable,' said Mr Charles Dolan, co-ordinator for the
Clinton campaign in Virginia, which is the next state to vote.
