FT  09 APR 92 / BBC World TV plans African venture
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BBC World Service Television is about to expand into Africa in a joint
venture with M-Net, the South African pay television service.
The 24-hours-a-day BBC television service now available by atellite to more
than 30 countries in Asia will begin broadcasting next week for 11 hours a
day to Africa and will be carried on an Intelsat satellite covering the
entire continent.
The encoded service will be aimed mainly at embassies, hotels, universities
and schools because a satellite dish of at least one metre diameter will be
needed to pick it up.
The BBC is also negotiating with a number of African broadcasting
organisations for the service to be re-broadcast over traditional
transmitters.
The move into Africa is part of the BBC's strategy to turn World Service
Television into a global service within the next two years to compete
head-on with Mr Ted Turner's Cable News Network.
M-Net is owned by Compagnie Financier Richemont, the corporate vehicle of
the Rupert family, which also owns Filmnet the European pay television
service. It will make available the satellite transponder that will carry
the BBC programmes and be responsible for marketing the service.
